## LLM Memory (ai-memory)

Durable project knowledge and the agent operating rules live in **ai-memory**,
recalled through the ai-memory MCP, scoped to this project by the operator-local
`.ai-memory.toml` marker (git-ignored). Recall before acting on durable
knowledge; write canonical findings back.

1. **Recall** the project's rules, decisions, and gotchas (`memory_query` /
   `memory_recent`) before proposing designs or explaining why something works
   a certain way.
2. **Read** a page directly (or `/api/v1`) when you already know its topic — a
   query hit's snippet is **not** the full body (large pages match outside the
   snippet window).
3. **Write back** — when you discover a canonical rule, gotcha, schema/contract,
   operational constraint, or product decision, persist it via
   `memory_write_page` and link related pages with `[[path.md]]` (paths carry
   the `.md` suffix; links resolve by exact path).

**Broaden when the current project misses.** `memory_query` searches only the
current project; there is no implicit global search. If recall comes back empty
or thin, the knowledge may live in a **sibling / shared project** (e.g. shared
`infra`, `ops`, or engineering rules) — re-run with explicit
`scopes: [{workspace, project}]`. Don't conclude "we never recorded it" after
one project misses.

Semantic decisions from conversation and debugging belong to the agent — recall
before acting, write back when you learn something canonical.
